### TITLE ###
TypedListIndexedAssignOk
### DESCRIPTION ###
`xs: int[]; xs[0] = 99` - assigning an int into an int[] passes
with no diagnostic. The element type matches.
### INPUT ###
xs: int[] = [1, 2, 3]
xs[0] = 99
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  xs @ 1:1 -> <no-type>
  xs @ 2:1 -> int[]

# Symbol types
  xs (local): int[]

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
TypedListIndexedAssignMismatch
### DESCRIPTION ###
`xs: int[]; xs[0] = "wrong"` fires
ErrCollectionElementMismatch - str is not assignable to the
declared int element type.
### INPUT ###
xs: int[] = [1, 2, 3]
xs[0] = "wrong"
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  xs @ 1:1 -> <no-type>
  xs @ 2:1 -> int[]

# Symbol types
  xs (local): int[]

# Diagnostics
  [hint] RAD30010 @ 2:9 - Value of type 'str' is not assignable to element type 'int'
### TITLE ###
TypedMapIndexedAssignOk
### DESCRIPTION ###
`m: { str: int }; m["k"] = 5` passes - int into int-valued map.
### INPUT ###
m: { str: int } = { "a": 1 }
m["b"] = 5
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  m @ 1:1 -> <no-type>
  m @ 2:1 -> { str: int }

# Symbol types
  m (local): { str: int }

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
TypedMapIndexedAssignMismatch
### DESCRIPTION ###
`m: { str: int }; m["k"] = "wrong"` fires - str is not assignable
to the map's int value type.
### INPUT ###
m: { str: int } = { "a": 1 }
m["b"] = "wrong"
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  m @ 1:1 -> <no-type>
  m @ 2:1 -> { str: int }

# Symbol types
  m (local): { str: int }

# Diagnostics
  [hint] RAD30010 @ 2:10 - Value of type 'str' is not assignable to element type 'int'
### TITLE ###
ParamIndexedAssignMismatch
### DESCRIPTION ###
Param-typed list also gets checked - fn param int[] flows through
to the assignment.
### INPUT ###
fn f(xs: int[]):
    xs[0] = "wrong"
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  xs @ 2:5 -> int[]

# Symbol types
  f (fn): fn(int[]) -> void
  xs (param): int[]

# Diagnostics
  [hint] RAD30010 @ 2:13 - Value of type 'str' is not assignable to element type 'int'
### TITLE ###
UntypedListSkipsCheck
### DESCRIPTION ###
`xs = [1, 2, 3]` has no annotation; the inferred type is `int[]`
but we deliberately don't fire on indexed assign here. The check
is opt-in via annotation - firing on inferred types would be
intrusive for scripts that build mixed lists gradually.
### INPUT ###
xs = [1, 2, 3]
xs[0] = "anything"
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  xs @ 1:1 -> <no-type>
  xs @ 2:1 -> int[]

# Symbol types
  xs (local): int[]

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
OpenListAnnotationSkipsCheck
### DESCRIPTION ###
`xs: list = ...` is the explicit "any element goes" form (AnyList),
distinct from `xs: int[]`. Indexed assign skips the check.
### INPUT ###
xs: list = [1, 2, 3]
xs[0] = "anything"
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  xs @ 1:1 -> <no-type>
  xs @ 2:1 -> int[]

# Symbol types
  xs (local): list

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
OpenMapAnnotationSkipsCheck
### DESCRIPTION ###
`m: map = ...` is the open map form. No element check.
### INPUT ###
m: map = { "a": 1 }
m["b"] = "anything"
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  m @ 1:1 -> <no-type>
  m @ 2:1 -> { str: int }

# Symbol types
  m (local): map

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
ChainedIndexedAssignSkipsCheck
### DESCRIPTION ###
Today we only check `<identifier>[i] = v` shape. Chained targets
like `m["a"][0] = v` skip silently - sound (we just don't catch a
mismatch we could've caught), and avoids depending on a full chain-
prefix type walker that's deferred.
### INPUT ###
fn f(m: { "a": int[] }):
    m["a"][0] = "wrong"
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  m @ 2:5 -> { "a": int[] }

# Symbol types
  f (fn): fn({ "a": int[] }) -> void
  m (param): { "a": int[] }

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
FieldAssignSkipsCheck
### DESCRIPTION ###
Struct-field assignment (`obj.field = v`) is a different mutation
surface and isn't part of Phase 6. No diagnostic.
### INPUT ###
fn f(obj: { "x": int }):
    obj.x = "wrong"
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  obj @ 2:5 -> { "x": int }

# Symbol types
  f (fn): fn({ "x": int }) -> void
  obj (param): { "x": int }

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
DynamicReceiverSkipsCheck
### DESCRIPTION ###
When the receiver synth's to Dynamic (forward reference,
unannotated param, etc.), we can't reason about the element type
and skip the check.
### INPUT ###
fn f(xs):
    xs[0] = "anything"
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  xs @ 2:5 -> dynamic

# Symbol types
  f (fn): fn(any) -> void
  xs (param): <no-type>

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
ErrorTypeRhsSuppresses
### DESCRIPTION ###
If the RHS already failed to check (ErrorType-poisoned), we don't
pile on a second diagnostic about the element type. One mistake,
one diagnostic.
### INPUT ###
xs: int[] = [1, 2, 3]
xs[0] = 1 + "not a number"
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  xs @ 1:1 -> <no-type>
  xs @ 2:1 -> int[]

# Symbol types
  xs (local): int[]

# Diagnostics
  [error] RAD30002 @ 2:9 - Invalid operand types: cannot do 'int + str'
    help: In v0.9, + no longer coerces types. Use string interpolation instead. See: https://amterp.dev/rad/migrations/v0.9/
### TITLE ###
NarrowedOptionalListChecks
### DESCRIPTION ###
`fn f(xs: int[]?)` declares an optional list. After `if xs != null:`
the frame narrows to `int[]`. The check uses the frame (more
precise than declared) so the mismatch still fires inside the guard.
### INPUT ###
fn f(xs: int[]?):
    if xs != null:
        xs[0] = "wrong"
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  xs @ 2:8 -> int[]?
  xs @ 3:9 -> int[]

# Symbol types
  f (fn): fn(int[]?) -> void
  xs (param): int[]?

# Diagnostics
  [hint] RAD30010 @ 3:17 - Value of type 'str' is not assignable to element type 'int'
